name: Anonymous
com:
>Build shelf/headboard onto couch
>65 dollars plus tip for 3 common boards
>make self sandwich to last a couple days
>5 dollars for a loaf of French bread, 12 dollars for a pound of turkey, 5 dollars for a jar of nice pickles, 4 dollars for half a pound of cheese
>end up spending like 22 dollars to make myself a sandwich once it's all together
It genuinely costs about the same to make shit for yourself than to just buy plastic shelves from Amazon and go to subway. The only advantage is quality. I could've spent 40 bucks on a shelving unit (made of MORE wood, finished and painted) from a thrift store, but I needed something that fit the space.
The strange thing is that an older item made of better material, more material, by an actual Carpenter, would've cost me less than 3 common boards held together with twine screws and l brackets. It doesn't apply to the sandwich but the shelves are already shelves and the wood has the potential to be anything. It could be a chair, or a barn, or even a house. There was a homeless guy who built himself a house in the middle of a street in Hollywood and it took him a week. It held together well enough and the boards were lined up right, and he wasn't in the cold where he was at. It would take you a hundred thousand dollars for something similar (tiny house on a patch of land, plus have to deal with taxes/permits). It isn't that hard to build a house, and it doesn't take that long, but someone wants you to work 30 years and sacrifice your soul to it, then make your kids do the same thing, and they're sucking up every bit of real actual (at least economic) potential in the country to do it. Whoever that person is they dangle a shack made of osb and white plastic paint in front of your face and expect you work your whole life for it, buy up all its raw materials, and make it illegal to build the same thing (or better) for yourself for good measure. Food is the same, and so is gas, and it's at best ignored and at worst celebrated.
